oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-29170-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Form a closed question by swapping the position of the verb and subject. Add a
  question word for an open question."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.356902Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-29170-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """In questions with reflexive verbs, only subject and verb swap position, and the
  reflexive pronoun follows the subject."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.356906Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-29170-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Modal (2-verb) questions swap the subject and 1st verb; the infinitive remains at
  the end."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.356910Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-29170-5
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """When describing a photo, use the acronym PALM. It stands for People, Action,
  Location, Mood. Add your own opinions too."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.356914Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-29161-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """All nouns in German start with a capital letter and have a grammatical gender,
  either masculine, feminine or neuter."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.357086Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-29161-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Many German nouns have plural forms, but many are used either only in the singular
  or the plural."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.357089Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-29161-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """There are nine rules for forming plurals in German. Plural rules should be learnt
  alongside the noun gender."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.357094Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-29161-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Weak and strong verbs have the same present tense endings; strong verbs change stem
  vowel for 'du' and 'er, sie, es'."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.357100Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-29161-5
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """German has one present tense which conveys both the English simple present and
  present continuous."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.357104Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-26584-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """The perfect tense in German takes a present tense form of the auxiliary verb and a
  past participle."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.357271Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-26584-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Weak verb past participles sandwich the stem with 'ge-' and '-t'. Strong verbs use
  'ge- and -'en'."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.357275Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-26584-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Put separable prefixes before the 'ge-', but there is no 'ge-' before inseparable
  prefixes or '-ieren' verbs."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.357279Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-26584-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Reflexive pronouns follow the auxiliary in WO1 and the subject in WO2. The German
  perfect has 2 English translations."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.357283Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-26584-5
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Use verb clauses in a conversation response, and extend answers with a different
  tense, subject, opinions and reasons."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.357287Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-29171-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """It is important to have a firm knowledge of sound-symbol correspondance to
  transcribe spoken German in a dictation."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.357291Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-29171-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """The most important thing for successful listening is a secure knowledge of
  vocabulary."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.357295Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-29171-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """As well as a broad vocabulary, prediction and being aware of distractors and
  synonyms are useful listening strategies."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.357299Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-29166-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Weak verbs form the imperfect tense by adding these endings to the verb stem: -te,
  -test, -te, -ten, -tet, -ten."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.357303Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-29166-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Strong verbs have irregular stems in the imperfect tense, with vowel changes and
  endings: -, st, -, en, t, en."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.357309Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-29166-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """The imperfect tense of ‘sein’, ‘haben’, modal verbs and 'es gab' are commonly used
  in spoken as well as written German."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.357313Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-29166-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "Use ‘früher’ with a past tense to mean ‘in the past’ or ‘used to’."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.357317Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-29166-5
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """The BORDER acronym is a useful tool to respond fully and accurately to bullet point
  writing prompts."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.357321Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-26601-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Word order 1 is the standard word order: subject-verb-object. Use WO1 after
  conjunctions 'und', 'oder', 'aber', 'denn'."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.358306Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-26601-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Word order 2 (inversion) is when subject and verb swap position so the verb is
  always the second idea in the sentence."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.358310Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-26601-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Word order 3 (subordination) is when the verb is sent to the end of the clause. Use
  WO3 after some conjunctions."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.358314Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-26601-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Use WO3 after: 'weil', 'obwohl', 'dass', 'wenn', 'ob', 'da', ‘bevor’, ‘als’,
  ‘nachdem’, ‘sobald’ and ‘falls’."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.358318Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-26601-5
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """When describing a photo, use the acronym PALM. It stands for People, Action,
  Location, Mood. Add your own opinions too."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.358322Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-29168-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """It is important to have a good knowledge of sound-symbol correspondences to
  accurately read aloud in German."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.358398Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-29168-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Look out for tricky sounds and cognates, and mentally rehearse before
  reading aloud."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.358402Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-29168-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """The most important thing for successful reading comprehension is a secure knowledge
  of vocabulary."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.358406Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-29168-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """It is also very helpful to look out for synonyms and distractors when answering
  reading comprehension questions."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.358412Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-29168-5
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """When translating, 'zoom in' to translate individual words and 'zoom out' to check
  the meaning of the whole sentence."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.358416Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-29187-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """When describing a photo, use the acronym PALM. It stands for People, Action,
  Location, Mood. Add your own opinions too."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.358499Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-29187-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "A well-developed response in conversation has at least three verb clauses."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.358504Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-29187-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Extend your answers by using a different tense, a different subject, or opinions and
  reasons."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.358509Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-29175-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Adjective endings change depending on the gender, case and number of the noun they
  describe."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.358514Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-29175-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Adjective endings also depend on whether they follow the definite article, the
  indefinite article or no article."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.358520Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-29175-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "Adjective agreement only occurs when the adjective comes before the noun."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.358524Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-29175-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "A well-developed response has at least three verb clauses."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.358528Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-29175-5
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Extend your answers by using a different tense, a different subject, or opinions and
  reasons."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.358532Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-26588-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Some verbs are followed by prepositions and the accusative case, and some are
  followed by prepositions and the dative."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.358759Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-26588-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Some nouns and adjectives are followed by set prepositions and cases, which, like
  the verbs, need to be learnt."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.358764Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-26588-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """The prefix 'da(r)-' can be added to prepositions to refer to something already
  mentioned. This is called a da- compound."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.358768Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-26588-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """When performing a role-play, answers should be a short phrase or sentence. Do not
  add unnecessary detail."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.358774Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-26588-5
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """It is helpful to categorise vocabulary by theme when revisiting large number of
  words."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.358778Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-26607-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """When describing a photo for the writing exam, focus on verb accuracy and clarity.
  Keep sentences short and simple."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.358918Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-26607-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """The BORDER acronym is a useful tool to respond fully and accurately to bullet point
  prompts in longer writing tasks."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.358925Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-26607-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """In extended writing, use subordinate clauses, relative clauses and infinitive
  constructions to extend sentences."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.358930Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-26607-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """When translating into German, translate the verb first, think about noun gender and
  check word order."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.358935Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-26607-5
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """When translating, account for the meaning of every word, but remember the message
  may not translate word-for-word."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.358939Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-26582-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """All nouns in German start with a capital letter and have a grammatical gender,
  either masculine, feminine or neuter."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.359186Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-26582-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Many German nouns have plural forms, but many are used either only in the singular
  or the plural."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.359192Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-26582-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """There are nine rules for forming plurals in German. Plural rules should be learnt
  alongside the noun gender."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.359196Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-26582-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Weak and strong verbs have the same present tense endings; strong verbs change stem
  vowel for 'du' and 'er, sie, es'."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.359200Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-26582-5
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """German has one present tense which conveys both the English simple present and
  present continuous."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.359206Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-26585-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Modal verbs are always followed by a 2nd infinitive verb which normally comes at the
  end of the sentence."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.359210Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-26585-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Modal verbs are irregular in the first, 2nd and 3rd person singular, but regular in
  plural forms."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.359216Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-26585-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Modal verbs are mostly used in the imperfect tense when they describe past events.
  Remove any umlauts in the imperfect."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.359220Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-26585-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """The imperfect tense endings for modal verbs (-te, -test, -te. -ten, -tet, -ten) are
  the same as for weak verbs."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.359224Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-26585-5
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """When performing a role-play, answers should be a short phrase or sentence. Do not
  add unnecessary detail."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.359228Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-29163-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """The perfect tense in German takes a present tense form of the auxiliary verb and a
  past participle."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.359284Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-29163-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Weak verb past participles sandwich the stem with 'ge-' and '-t'. Strong verbs use
  'ge- and -'en'."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.359288Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-29163-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Put separable prefixes before the 'ge-', but there is no 'ge-' before inseparable
  prefixes or '-ieren' verbs."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.359292Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-29163-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Reflexive pronouns follow the auxiliary in WO1 and the subject in WO2. The German
  perfect has 2 English translations."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.359296Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-29163-5
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Use verb clauses in a conversation response, and extend answers with a different
  tense, subject, opinions and reasons."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.359299Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-29162-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """A firm knowledge of German sound-symbol correspondence is important to transcribe
  spoken German in a dictation."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.359303Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-29162-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """The most important thing for successful listening is a secure knowledge of
  vocabulary."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.359307Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-29162-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """As well as a broad vocabulary, prediction and being aware of distractors and
  synonyms are useful listening strategies"""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.359311Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-29178-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Add the suffix -ung to a verb stem to form a feminine noun with equivalent meaning,
  e.g., 'lösen' - 'die Lösung'."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.359315Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-29178-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Add suffix -er to a verb stem to form a male agent noun with equivalent meaning,
  e.g., 'übersetzen' - 'der Übersetzer'."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.359319Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-29178-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Add the suffix -keit / -heit to adjectives to form feminine nouns meaning -ty or
  -ness, e.g., 'krank' - 'die Krankheit'."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.359323Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-29178-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Add the suffix -chen or -lein to a noun to mean 'little'. These diminutive nouns are
  neuter and often gain an umlaut."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.359327Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-29178-5
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Extend answers in conversation to 3 clauses by using a different tense, a different
  subject, or opinions and reasons."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.359331Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-29184-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """When describing a photo for the writing exam, focus on verb accuracy and clarity.
  Keep sentences short and simple."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.359766Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-29184-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """The BORDER acronym is a useful tool to respond fully and accurately to bullet point
  prompts in longer writing tasks."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.359770Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-29184-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """In extended writing, use subordinate clauses, relative clauses and infinitive
  constructions to extend sentences."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.359774Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-29184-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """When translating into German, translate the verb first, think about noun gender and
  check word order."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.359794Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-29184-5
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """When translating, account for the meaning of every word, but remember the message
  may not translate word-for-word."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.359799Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-26593-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """To form a question in the perfect tense, swap the auxiliary verb 'haben' or 'sein'
  with the subject."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.359952Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-26593-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """To form a question in the future tense, swap the part of 'werden' with the subject.
  The infinitive stays at the end."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.359957Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-26593-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """In a conversation, you can usually use the question to start your answer. Change 2nd
  person language to 1st person."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.359961Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-26593-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "A well-developed response has at least three verb clauses."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.359981Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-26593-5
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Extend your answers by using a different tense, a different subject, or opinions and
  reasons."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.359985Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-26589-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """It is important to have a good knowledge of sound-symbol correspondences to
  accurately read aloud in German."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.360226Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-26589-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Look out for tricky sounds and cognates, and mentally rehearse before
  reading aloud."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.360230Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-26589-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """The most important thing for successful reading comprehension is a secure knowledge
  of vocabulary."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.360234Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-26589-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """It is also very helpful to look out for synonyms and distractors when answering
  reading comprehension questions."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.360238Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-26589-5
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """When translating, 'zoom in' to translate individual words and 'zoom out' to check
  the meaning of the whole sentence."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.360242Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-29180-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """It is important to have a good knowledge of sound-symbol correspondences to
  accurately read aloud in German."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:29.360763Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

